A cursory look at the problems buffeting us and the lopsided priorities of our leadership tells us that though we may be maturing as a nation, we are still, like babes, mindlessly tottering towards an abyss.
National days like Jamhuri should be occasions for soul-searching and stock-taking. There are ample reasons to doubt that we do that, which is why too many people are giving in to pessimism.
Nurses’ strike
Right now, we are in the midst of a strike by nurses and clinicians. These grievances have consistently been ignored by the authorities, even after seven months of a worsening global pandemic.





In the next 10 days, unless there is urgent intervention, doctors will join the strike. What then happens to the millions of poor Kenyans being denied medical attention?
To paraphrase a politician I used to admire, it is the government’s duty to provide basic needs to the vulnerable, among them affordable health services, water and sanitation, education, housing and food.
Taking stock would entail looking at all these needs and how they have been handled in the past three decades, and so far, the record has been abysmal, though to be sure, our leaders always talk about their urgency.
What seems to be the problem? Two major hurdles, it appears, always stand in the way of their fulfilment—ceaseless jostling for political power and mind-numbing corruption.



