However, in another sense, things cannot be as bleak as they appear on the surface. We, indeed, have come far from those days when our parents struggled against colonial rule, and although the country is still among the least developed in the world, those who complain that we were better off at Independence are spouting self-serving propaganda for argument’s sake.
We may not be where we should be after 57 years of self-rule, but we are not yet a failed state. Nor shall we, hopefully, be in the near future, for we are a fairly resilient society.
However, unless things change, it will be a near thing. Last Saturday, I was privileged to join a number of fellow elders at a relative’s bride price ceremony. It was actually nothing more than a formal recognition of an already existing union, so we didn’t have to negotiate a reasonable deal, and all we had to do was to make witty speeches, pray, praise and eat.
Poverty
However, I was more interested in investigating my surroundings and finding out how other people live and was puzzled at the level of poverty I saw in an otherwise verdant environment.
Tucked somewhere about seven kilometres from Gatundu town in Kiambu County is a nondescript settlement that’s famous for nothing at all except that its dwellers grow Kenya’s favourite beverage, tea, in huge quantities.



