However, few of those I saw at Gitwe seem to have benefited at all from the crop, though there is a leaf collection centre nearby and lorry-loads of the commodity are daily transported there. It appears the majority of the dwellers missed out on the Kenyan dream while a few made it big – very big.
I sought to understand why the high levels of poverty amid such lush greenery, but then it occurred to me that what I was seeing was an illusion; ordinary farmers do not own any of the plantations.
 Indeed, the majority spend their days plucking tea leaves for meagre wages, while even the small growers who do own plots under tea are not much better off, for when they send their produce to the collection centres they are usually robbed blind at every stage of the process and forced to lead a precarious hand-to-mouth existence.
This anecdote serves to illustrate one important truth; national holidays are increasingly becoming irrelevant in people’s lives but their leaders do not know it. When I cheekily sought to know from a group of shabby individuals I accosted in the locality’s tiny shopping centre how they planned to celebrate Jamhuri Day, the response was explosive.
“What is Jamhuri? You tycoons from Nairobi can go ahead and celebrate. Tell Uhuru the children are still at home since March and there is no food for them.”



